erican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Andres, Manuel, Alba, Ana, Ana Milena, Bernardo, Cosme, Elena, Enrique, Esperanza, Eugenio, Gregorio.","Catalan (<b>Borràs</b>): from the personal name <i>Borràs</i>, of unexplained etymology."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":24,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Andrew Borlas was born about 1358, in Cornwall, England, his father, Noel De Borlase, was 34 and his mother, Agnes De Trevysek, was 35. He had at least 2 sons with Amicia Fowey. He died about 1414, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 58."},"et":{"c1358–about 1414":"umbes 1358–umbes 1414","1350–Male":"13